            <handDesc>
              <handNote xml:id="winithar-brown" scope="major" medium="brown-ink" scribe="Winithar">Main
                text copied by the scribe Winithar in dark brown ink. The script is an
                idiosyncratic, early form of &lt;term ref="#alemannic-minuscule"&gt;Alemannic
                minuscule&lt;/term&gt;, exhibiting a heavy, slightly uncalligraphic
                &lt;term&gt;ductus&lt;/term&gt;. Diagnostic features include the frequent use of the
                open &lt;term&gt;cc-a&lt;/term&gt;, fractured or clubbed
                &lt;term&gt;minims&lt;/term&gt;, and the distinctive downward-sweeping crossbar of
                the letter t.</handNote>
              <handNote xml:id="winithar-orange" scope="minor" medium="orange-ink" scribe="Winithar">Rubrications,
                incipits, and highlighted initials executed by Winithar in a distinctive orange (or
                reddish-orange) ink . The morphological features of the script remain identical to
                &lt;ref target="#winithar-brown"&gt;his main text hand&lt;/ref&gt;, confirming that
                the change in medium is purely for structural and navigational emphasis within the
                codex rather than a change in scribe.</handNote>
            </handDesc>
          </physDesc>
          <history>
            <origin>
              <p>Written at the Abbey of St. Gall by the monk and scribe Winithar. Dated to <origDate
                  notBefore="0760" notAfter="0764">c. 760-764</origDate> based on paleographical
                evidence and Winithar's known period of activity.</p>
            </origin>
            <provenance>
              <p>The manuscript is indigenous to St. Gall. It has remained in the continuous
                possession of the <orgName>Stiftsbibliothek St. Gallen</orgName> (Abbey Library of
                St. Gall) since its creation in the eighth century.</p>
            </provenance>
          </history>
        </msDesc>
